04:05.491 --> 04:08.458
<i>♪ And it's just time ♪</i>

04:08.494 --> 04:09.526
<i>♪ Every day ♪</i>

04:09.561 --> 04:11.528
<i>♪ We find ourselves ♪</i>

04:11.563 --> 04:13.997
<i>♪ A little further down the line ♪</i>

04:14.033 --> 04:18.168
<i>♪ I'm going to California ♪</i>

04:18.202 --> 04:20.103
<i>♪ By myself... ♪</i>

04:20.139 --> 04:22.105
[Bill] Phil, what can you tell me

04:22.141 --> 04:24.041
about the European leg of the tour?

04:24.076 --> 04:28.512
- 'Cause I'd heard that...
- Shh, Dead Sex.

04:28.547 --> 04:30.113
I think Jen's alive.

04:30.149 --> 04:31.648
[Rick] <i>Harris DeSoto,</i>

04:31.684 --> 04:34.451
<i>Rick Davidson, head
of search operations.</i>

04:34.486 --> 04:36.453
Remember how surly you got with me

04:36.488 --> 04:38.722
when you told me that
she died in the Plague?

04:38.757 --> 04:40.157
Remember that?

04:40.192 --> 04:41.725
I knew you were wrong.

04:41.760 --> 04:44.628
God, do I hate
myself for loving this show.

04:44.663 --> 04:46.229
But it's goddamn powerful stuff.

04:46.265 --> 04:47.731
<i>You can't escape us, Harris.</i>

04:47.766 --> 04:50.233
<i>Now, we need to take
you back to the center</i>

04:50.269 --> 04:52.669
<i>to have sex to see if
there is hope for the rest of us</i>

04:52.705 --> 04:54.371
<i>and for the future.</i>

04:54.406 --> 04:57.140
It's embarrassing, you
and me watching this,

04:57.176 --> 04:58.875
two grown men.

04:58.911 --> 05:02.312
<i>None of you understand the burden</i>

05:02.348 --> 05:06.049
<i>of having to father an
entire new generation.</i>

05:06.085 --> 05:07.818
I mean, well, we should be watching

05:07.853 --> 05:09.653
a documentary or something.

05:09.688 --> 05:13.156
Yeah, a documentary...

05:13.192 --> 05:16.059
<i>about the making of Dead Sex.</i>

05:16.095 --> 05:17.761
[Harris] <i>I'm not a god.</i>

05:23.969 --> 05:25.569
[sighs]

05:25.604 --> 05:27.204
It's gonna be a long one tonight.

05:27.239 --> 05:28.872
That's what I told my old lady

05:28.907 --> 05:31.108
the first time we were
about to get naked.

05:33.645 --> 05:38.615
Gooch, I'm coming to
you with a... a problem.

05:38.650 --> 05:40.951
About what happens when this tour ends?

05:40.986 --> 05:42.786
How did you know that?

05:42.821 --> 05:44.221
It's in the air, baby.

05:44.256 --> 05:46.056
Nobody has a retainer but Shelli.

05:46.091 --> 05:48.358
That means this whole
crew could break up, you know.

05:48.394 --> 05:49.738
They could find cheaper
people in Europe.

05:49.762 --> 05:51.695
That does happen.

05:51.730 --> 05:53.897
I'm just really fucking worried
that I'm gonna lose

05:53.932 --> 05:57.734
something special, you know?

05:57.770 --> 06:00.470
This feeling on this tour.

06:00.506 --> 06:02.706
Yeah, you know, you say that,

06:02.741 --> 06:04.574
but what I'm hearing is,

06:04.610 --> 06:07.244
"What am I gonna do without Kelly Ann?"

06:07.279 --> 06:10.080
- Yes.
- Let her go, Milo.

06:10.115 --> 06:13.917
She already traded you
in for a real Englishman.

06:13.952 --> 06:15.152
No... no, she didn't.

06:15.187 --> 06:17.120
That... that's just, like, a rumor.

06:17.156 --> 06:19.556
Look, you're
good-looking. Plus, you're tall.

06:19.591 --> 06:21.825
And lately you've been smelling
moderately better.

06:21.860 --> 06:23.160
Thanks.

06:23.195 --> 06:24.005
I mean, look, there's no reason

06:24.007 --> 06:26.441
why you can't find
someone that's wonderful

06:26.465 --> 06:29.232
and equally odd.

06:29.268 --> 06:31.134
I don't want this tour to end.

06:31.170 --> 06:32.914
[Wesley] <i>All right, take
it away, West Coast.</i>

06:32.938 --> 06:34.805
[upbeat, twangy music playing on guitar]

06:34.840 --> 06:36.473
<i>All right, y'all, I got it from here.</i>

06:36.508 --> 06:37.974
One, two, three.

06:38.010 --> 06:39.609
♪ Now, beer, beer, beer, beer ♪

06:39.645 --> 06:41.611
♪ I can find it near or far ♪

06:41.647 --> 06:43.487
♪ And I drink my beer out
of cans and bottles ♪

06:43.515 --> 06:45.126
♪ Shit, I'll drink
it out of this guitar ♪

06:45.150 --> 06:47.017
- ♪ Guitar ♪
- ♪ Now, I love beer ♪

06:47.052 --> 06:49.286
♪ And you love beer, man,
fuck it, so does Bill ♪

06:49.321 --> 06:50.754
♪ Bill doesn't drink anymore ♪

06:50.789 --> 06:52.456
♪ But he did when he saw Phil ♪

06:52.491 --> 06:55.492
[laughter]

06:57.496 --> 07:00.163
Oh.

07:00.199 --> 07:05.001
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:05.037 --> 07:07.370
Have you heard any more
about the European dates?

07:07.406 --> 07:08.144
No.

07:08.299 --> 07:10.785
- Everybody's asking, though.
- Tell me about it.

07:10.809 --> 07:12.550
- [Wesley] All right.
- [woman] All right.

07:12.551 --> 07:14.355
[Wesley] ♪ Give me a
joint, and give me a fire ♪

07:14.379 --> 07:16.480
♪ Hell, I don't need no amplifier ♪

07:16.515 --> 07:19.382
♪ 'Cause one of these beers
right here will turn me up ♪

07:19.418 --> 07:21.651
♪ We got 12 more hours on this bus ♪

07:21.687 --> 07:23.487
♪ And sorry, Phil, I
don't mean to cuss ♪

07:23.522 --> 07:26.122
♪ But God damn it, Gooch, hurry up ♪

07:26.158 --> 07:27.324
[Milo] Yeah!

07:27.359 --> 07:30.227
Ahh, this is gonna get old.

07:30.262 --> 07:32.896
<i>[mellow rock music]</i>

07:32.931 --> 07:34.909
What are you gonna do when
this tour ends, Kelly Ann?

07:34.933 --> 07:36.466
[Kelly Ann] Hmm.

07:36.502 --> 07:39.369
I don't know.

07:39.404 --> 07:41.805
I mean, the band's holding
dates in Europe,

07:41.840 --> 07:43.073
unless they bag 'em.

07:43.108 --> 07:45.041
I bet our boy with Extantion

07:45.077 --> 07:46.387
has got something to do with that.

07:46.411 --> 07:48.345
He's in the front with Harvey right now.

07:48.380 --> 07:50.914
I don't care if he's up my
ass making shepherd's pie.

07:50.949 --> 07:53.216
The end of the tour reveals all.

07:53.252 --> 07:56.820
He's going over the
financials right now on this very bus,

07:56.855 --> 07:58.399
who gets a retainer,
what vendors get cut.

07:58.423 --> 07:59.341
It's true.

07:59.498 --> 08:01.691
I think it's all being decided tonight.

08:01.727 --> 08:04.561
I can smell it coming like
a steak house fart.

08:04.596 --> 08:05.907
Kelly Ann, you're the only person

08:05.931 --> 08:07.430
who'd get the truth out of Reg.

08:07.466 --> 08:09.332
I got to know if I'm still on this tour.

08:09.368 --> 08:10.834
I got Halsey's people calling.

08:10.869 --> 08:13.570
Apparently, she's
trying to steal our whole crew.

08:13.605 --> 08:17.641
<i>♪ I can't sit or stand around... ♪</i>

08:19.711 --> 08:21.678
- Hi.
- Hi.

08:21.713 --> 08:25.949
Reg, I think you need to tell
everybody who's gonna be hired

08:25.984 --> 08:28.718
to go on the European leg, 'cause...

08:28.754 --> 08:30.554
I just think people
are really desperate.

08:30.589 --> 08:32.900
Well, now, I just... I just assumed
that everyone was going.

08:32.924 --> 08:35.203
It never occurred to me that...
That everyone wouldn't go.

08:35.227 --> 08:37.409
I just assumed that it
would continue intact

08:37.446 --> 08:39.763
with the, uh... With the same crew.

08:39.798 --> 08:42.076
At least that was the... that
was the recommendation that I made.

08:42.100 --> 08:44.234
- You did?
- Yeah.

08:44.269 --> 08:47.804
Thanks, this will really
soothe the crew.

08:47.839 --> 08:48.922
Yeah.

08:48.957 --> 08:50.006
Ooh.

08:53.178 --> 08:54.694
- Harvey.
- Kelly Ann.

08:54.730 --> 08:57.697
<i>[upbeat bluesy rock music]</i>

08:57.733 --> 08:59.249
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:59.284 --> 09:02.702
Hey, Phil, can I ask
you a naive, silly question?

09:02.738 --> 09:04.437
I'd be surprised if you didn't.

09:04.473 --> 09:06.117
[Wesley] How'd you
get mixed up in all this,

09:06.141 --> 09:08.942
you know, like, the
music and the touring

09:08.977 --> 09:10.443
and the badassery?

09:10.479 --> 09:13.597
Well, we don't have
time on a 12-hour bus ride

09:13.632 --> 09:15.782
to fully answer that question,

09:15.817 --> 09:19.603
but the short answer is this.

09:19.638 --> 09:20.820
You don't pick it.

09:20.856 --> 09:22.672
It picks you.

09:22.708 --> 09:25.508
Okay, but who was the best, Phil?

09:25.544 --> 09:28.845
I mean, who was your band?

09:31.617 --> 09:33.800
Nah, I got to be in the right mood.

09:33.835 --> 09:35.802
What the fuck mood are
you waiting for, man?

09:35.837 --> 09:38.488
We're on a bus for 12
hours. Just tell the story.

09:38.523 --> 09:40.702
Yeah, well, you got to have
a few more rings on your tree

09:40.726 --> 09:43.760
before you can push a
button and demand my expertise.

09:43.795 --> 09:46.429
Phil...

09:46.465 --> 09:47.914
tell the story.

09:47.950 --> 09:49.466
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:49.501 --> 09:51.418
All right.

09:51.453 --> 09:52.669
[laughs] Nice.

09:52.704 --> 09:54.654
Now, to tell this story properly,

09:54.690 --> 09:56.940
I got to introduce you to a man,

09:56.975 --> 09:58.441
my father.

09:58.477 --> 10:00.593
They ran a bait shop.

10:00.629 --> 10:02.979
<i>I used to hang out in
the back from a young age,</i>

10:03.015 --> 10:06.933
<i>and I definitely new this,
at my father's back office,</i>

10:06.969 --> 10:08.818
<i>they never talked about bait.</i>

10:08.854 --> 10:12.522
Fellas, I can't make it to
Atlanta with the cigars.

10:12.557 --> 10:14.691
I mean, who is this guy?

10:14.726 --> 10:16.826
He's a promoter, Vince Packard.

10:16.862 --> 10:19.663
He works with rock bands.

10:19.698 --> 10:22.298
We just need someone to
drive them to him in Atlanta.

10:22.334 --> 10:24.467
He's been a big customer.

10:24.503 --> 10:27.003
- He needs 'em tonight.
- I'll go.

10:27.039 --> 10:29.172
[Phil Sr.] You know, I
remember this guy Packard

10:29.207 --> 10:32.575
back from when we had that Asian Zircon

10:32.611 --> 10:36.046
mail-order situation going.

10:36.081 --> 10:39.349
Pop, let me go.

10:39.384 --> 10:43.853
Son, you may be on to something.

10:45.741 --> 10:47.724
No one would think twice about him

10:47.759 --> 10:50.060
crossing any state line.

10:50.095 --> 10:52.395
[Les] Well, you're right.

10:52.431 --> 10:54.514
Just look at that honest face.

10:54.549 --> 10:56.166
[Phil] <i>Well, the next thing I know,</i>

10:56.201 --> 10:59.602
I'm delivering a big
box to a promoter in Atlanta

10:59.638 --> 11:01.104
doing a show at the Omni.

11:01.139 --> 11:05.175
Now, it's The Who and Lynyrd Skynyrd.

11:05.210 --> 11:07.944
Now, I don't know
music at all, all right?

11:07.979 --> 11:10.413
But I'm nervous, but I'm excited.

11:10.449 --> 11:13.450
Right before I leave,
my dad says, "Listen..."

11:13.485 --> 11:14.901
Make sure you get paid, okay?

11:14.936 --> 11:17.670
It'll be in a yellow envelope.

11:17.706 --> 11:22.692
Uh, Father, am I doing
something illegal?

11:22.728 --> 11:26.446
Would I let my own
son do something illegal?

11:26.481 --> 11:29.849
[Vince] <i>Ah, the illegal
Havanas are here.</i>

11:29.885 --> 11:31.785
All right.

11:32.888 --> 11:34.304
Thanks, kid.

11:34.339 --> 11:36.456
All right, you enjoy
that show, all right?

11:36.491 --> 11:37.969
Uh, well, I-I need a yellow envelope.

11:37.993 --> 11:39.470
It's all taken care of. Enjoy the show.

11:39.494 --> 11:41.828
B-but Father said that
I need an e-envelope.

11:43.932 --> 11:45.265
Mr. Packard.

11:45.300 --> 11:47.233
<i>♪ Ooh-ooh ♪</i>

11:47.269 --> 11:50.570
<i>♪ Ooh-ooh-ah ♪</i>

11:50.605 --> 11:52.739
<i>♪ Double beating... ♪</i>

11:52.774 --> 11:56.443
[Phil] <i>Sometimes destiny has a way</i>

11:56.478 --> 11:59.712
<i>of walking right into you,</i>

11:59.748 --> 12:02.315
<i>walking right through you.</i>

12:02.350 --> 12:04.100
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:06.838 --> 12:09.122
Uh, Mr. Packard,

12:09.157 --> 12:11.074
I was thinking about our conversation,

12:11.109 --> 12:13.276
and I know for sure that
you're supposed to give me

12:13.311 --> 12:16.446
reciprocation in a yellow envelope.

12:16.481 --> 12:18.164
I don't know what you're talking about.

12:18.200 --> 12:19.849
I'm quite sure that I'm right.

12:19.885 --> 12:21.067
Excuse me.

12:21.103 --> 12:22.852
My name's Ronnie Van Zant.

12:22.888 --> 12:26.289
My band Lynyrd Skynyrd's opening
up tonight for The Who.

12:26.324 --> 12:29.492
If you owe this man
something, you've given him your word,

12:29.528 --> 12:31.027
you should pay him.

12:31.062 --> 12:34.931
Otherwise, I got no
reason to play for you tonight

12:34.966 --> 12:36.666
or ever.

12:36.701 --> 12:39.435
Now, do what's right.

12:39.471 --> 12:41.437
You really want to get involved in this?

12:41.473 --> 12:43.273
Oh, yes, sir. I do.

12:43.308 --> 12:45.203
And I got a whole bunch of
people out there with me

12:45.227 --> 12:47.744
who feel the same way.

12:51.650 --> 12:55.285
Shit, I was always gonna pay him.

12:55.320 --> 12:56.719
Right now.

12:59.858 --> 13:01.791
Come to my office.

13:01.827 --> 13:03.404
<i>[Lynyrd Skynyrd's "Gimme
Three Steps" playing]</i>

13:03.428 --> 13:05.995
I'd wash that jacket if I were you.

13:06.031 --> 13:07.831
<i>What's your name?</i>

13:07.866 --> 13:09.232
Phil.

13:09.267 --> 13:10.900
Phil.

13:10.936 --> 13:12.880
You better just go on home before
somebody comes after you

13:12.904 --> 13:14.871
with a loaded firearm.

13:14.906 --> 13:16.873
Your luck ain't pretty tonight.

13:16.908 --> 13:18.508
Oh, I think it is.

13:18.543 --> 13:20.009
I appreciate you getting me paid,

13:20.045 --> 13:23.346
and sorry about your black eye.

13:23.381 --> 13:26.349
I don't know much, but I
know when somebody sounds honest

13:26.384 --> 13:29.802
and when they don't, and
you sounded honest.

13:29.838 --> 13:32.805
Well, I-I look forward to
enjoying your music sometime.

13:32.858 --> 13:34.657
No time like the present.

13:34.693 --> 13:37.560
I got to get back to Texas
and help my dad run his bait shop.

13:37.596 --> 13:39.062
Playing Fort Worth tomorrow.

13:39.097 --> 13:40.663
[Phil] <i>I was with 'em for three days,</i>

13:40.699 --> 13:42.899
<i>and I'd never seen anything like it.</i>

13:42.934 --> 13:46.336
Lynyrd Skynyrd would
play these amazing sets

13:46.371 --> 13:49.038
<i>and then go find the
perfectly wrong bar.</i>

13:49.074 --> 13:52.041
[all speaking indistinctly]

13:52.077 --> 13:54.177
<i>[upbeat country rock music]</i>

13:54.212 --> 13:56.429
<i>♪ Well, I pulled out of Pittsburgh... ♪</i>

13:56.464 --> 13:57.914
What kind of place is this?

13:57.949 --> 13:59.377
Are you sure you don't want a drink?

13:59.401 --> 14:01.117
Oh, no, I don't... I don't drink.

14:01.152 --> 14:03.253
Well, you can't say
no if you never tried it.

14:03.288 --> 14:05.171
Oh, well, I don't need to try it.

14:05.207 --> 14:08.341
You should meet a gentleman
by the name of Mr. Jack Daniel's.

14:08.376 --> 14:11.411
<i>♪ But I don't see a cop in sight ♪</i>

14:11.446 --> 14:13.263
<i>♪ Six days on the road ♪</i>

14:13.298 --> 14:17.517
<i>♪ And I'm gonna make
it home tonight... ♪</i>

14:17.552 --> 14:20.053
- [coughs]
- It's good stuff, right?

14:20.088 --> 14:22.305
Ooh!

14:22.340 --> 14:23.606
You got a girl back home?

14:23.625 --> 14:25.525
I sure do.

14:25.560 --> 14:29.462
She's mean as hell, but I love her.

14:31.099 --> 14:32.949
You gonna marry her?

14:32.984 --> 14:33.933
If I'm lucky.

14:33.969 --> 14:36.869
[laughs]

14:36.905 --> 14:38.955
Oh, I like Jack Daniel's.

14:38.990 --> 14:40.373
So does he.

14:40.408 --> 14:43.309
You Lynyrd Skynyrd?

14:43.345 --> 14:47.797
You tough guys think you
can come in here and drink?

14:47.832 --> 14:51.935
Your band ain't shit compared
to The Allman Brothers Band.

14:51.970 --> 14:54.070
You may be right about that.

14:54.105 --> 14:55.238
Easy. We ain't gonna fight.

14:55.273 --> 14:56.773
You ain't gonna fight?

14:56.808 --> 14:59.125
How can you live with
being a hypocrite, man?

14:59.160 --> 15:01.961
I read about you guys being so tough.

15:01.997 --> 15:04.514
I don't see nothing!

15:04.549 --> 15:06.182
Excuse me,

15:06.217 --> 15:08.017
but you're bothering Mr. Van Zant.

15:08.053 --> 15:11.321
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:11.356 --> 15:13.523
I don't mean nothing.

15:13.558 --> 15:16.125
<i>♪ But I could never make
believe it's all right ♪</i>

15:16.161 --> 15:17.293
<i>♪ Six days on the road... ♪</i>

15:17.329 --> 15:18.494
Look at that.

15:18.530 --> 15:20.034
The hell got into you?

15:20.193 --> 15:22.877
I don't know what got into me,
except he was being an asshole.

15:22.901 --> 15:25.501
Whatever it was,
boy, I'd hang on to that.

15:25.537 --> 15:27.570
Oh, I just did what came naturally.

15:29.000 --> 15:35.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

15:50.996 --> 15:51.961
- Hey.
- Hey.

15:51.997 --> 15:53.229
Reg.

15:59.104 --> 16:01.537
Harvey, come and look at this.

16:06.344 --> 16:09.245
I don't know.

16:09.280 --> 16:11.814
There's no easy answer, is there?

16:11.850 --> 16:14.684
[Phil] <i>And they had about
five solid hits under their belt,</i>

16:14.719 --> 16:17.353
great songs, and the one
true classic, "Freebird."

16:17.389 --> 16:18.588
Right.

16:18.623 --> 16:21.758
But in the day, everywhere Skynyrd went,

16:21.793 --> 16:24.660
one of the guys would get
drunk or somebody'd get drunk,

16:24.696 --> 16:28.097
and the shit would start flying.

16:28.133 --> 16:31.834
And it was for that as much
as their songs they became known.

16:31.870 --> 16:34.904
And that's all anybody outside
the band wanted to do

16:34.939 --> 16:36.873
or talk about was fighting.

16:36.908 --> 16:38.441
Is that when you started drinking?

16:38.476 --> 16:42.345
Well, Mr. Jack Daniel's
and I have had a love affair

16:42.380 --> 16:44.914
that has lasted to this very day,

16:44.949 --> 16:48.017
but he holds nothing compared
to the feelings I had

16:48.053 --> 16:49.252
out on the road.

16:49.287 --> 16:50.553
[Phil Sr.] Lynyrd who?

16:50.588 --> 16:52.055
It's a band, Pop.

16:52.090 --> 16:54.857
It's... it's a group
of people from Florida,

16:54.893 --> 16:57.060
and I enjoy their company.

16:57.095 --> 17:00.063
<i>[Lynyrd Skynyrd's "T For Texas" playing]</i>

17:00.098 --> 17:03.466
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:03.501 --> 17:07.103
I raised you to be my partner.

17:07.137 --> 17:09.872
I found something else I like better.

17:09.907 --> 17:12.875
<i>I left home for 18 months</i>

17:12.911 --> 17:16.779
<i>while Skynyrd toured every
city you can imagine.</i>

17:16.815 --> 17:19.281
<i>Now, Ronnie had a foolproof method</i>

17:19.317 --> 17:21.584
<i>for clearing up the hangovers.</i>

17:21.618 --> 17:24.921
<i>Pure oxygen can cure a
hangover in five minutes.</i>

17:24.955 --> 17:27.323
<i>♪ Give me a T For Texas ♪</i>

17:27.358 --> 17:30.093
<i>♪ Give me a T for Tennessee... ♪</i>

17:30.128 --> 17:33.596
I barely made it home for
the birth of Vernon, my son,

17:33.631 --> 17:36.065
and, boy, was Ella mad.

17:36.101 --> 17:38.067
I still got the picture in my wallet.

17:38.103 --> 17:39.302
Let's see.

17:41.840 --> 17:43.940
Yeah, she looks fucking pissed.

17:43.975 --> 17:46.275
[laughter]

17:46.311 --> 17:49.312
Well, I had the
problem that we all have.

17:49.347 --> 17:52.148
What, you didn't
particularly want to go home?

17:52.183 --> 17:54.283
- [Phil]
Exactly. - Mm-hmm.

17:54.319 --> 17:56.652
I became the assistant road manager

17:56.688 --> 17:59.622
known to many a hotel manager.

17:59.657 --> 18:01.757
I became indispensable to 'em.

18:01.793 --> 18:03.003
[woman] They smashed my lights,

18:03.027 --> 18:06.529
two tables, and my neon sign.

18:06.564 --> 18:07.997
That's $1,000.

18:08.032 --> 18:11.701
Oh, well, I'm here to settle the bill.

18:11.736 --> 18:14.170
<i>And then came the Canada incident.</i>

18:14.205 --> 18:16.639
<i>Ron Eckerman and the
assistant road manager,</i>

18:16.674 --> 18:18.875
<i>Dean Kilpatrick, and I told everybody</i>

18:18.910 --> 18:21.711
<i>not to bring any drugs, I mean nothing,</i>

18:21.746 --> 18:23.124
<i>and everybody threw everything away</i>

18:23.148 --> 18:24.981
<i>back in the States.</i>

18:25.016 --> 18:27.483
<i>Did you see what they wrote
about us in CIRCUS magazine?</i>

18:27.519 --> 18:29.552
"They'll fight anybody anywhere."

18:29.587 --> 18:30.953
Who puts this stuff out there?

18:30.989 --> 18:32.522
I don't know, Ronnie.

18:32.557 --> 18:35.892
All I do know is that everybody
likes a bad boy.

18:35.927 --> 18:38.127
- You might be right about that.
- Mm-hmm.

18:38.163 --> 18:39.495
<i>I felt respected by 'em,</i>

18:39.531 --> 18:42.465
you know, part of the family.

18:42.500 --> 18:44.200
[Billy] <i>Hey, Phil.</i>

18:44.235 --> 18:45.535
- Phil.
- What?

18:45.570 --> 18:47.904
Could you hold my bag?

18:47.939 --> 18:48.971
Sure, brother.

18:49.007 --> 18:50.139
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:50.175 --> 18:53.009
<i>♪ Give me a T for Thelma ♪</i>

18:53.044 --> 18:55.511
<i>♪ Woman made a fool out of me ♪</i>

18:55.547 --> 18:58.347
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:58.383 --> 18:59.749
<i>♪ Give me a T... ♪</i>

18:59.784 --> 19:01.384
[Phil] <i>Now, I knew at that moment</i>

19:01.419 --> 19:03.486
<i>I was ready to go to
jail for these boys,</i>

19:03.521 --> 19:06.556
'cause I believed.

19:06.591 --> 19:08.257
But I sure wasn't comfortable.

19:08.293 --> 19:10.660
We found cocaine, quaaludes,

19:10.695 --> 19:12.562
a lot of seed-filled marijuana.

19:12.597 --> 19:15.765
Now, something tells me that
doesn't all belong to you.

19:15.800 --> 19:18.000
You don't even have to speak.

19:18.036 --> 19:20.703
Just nod your head, and you walk.

19:20.738 --> 19:24.707
Does this bag belong to the band?

19:24.742 --> 19:28.411
Sir, I'm gonna tell you the truth.

19:28.446 --> 19:31.781
Now, the leader of this
band, whose bag this is not,

19:31.816 --> 19:34.417
will be greatly
affected by this incident,

19:34.452 --> 19:37.019
and I believe him to be one
of the finest gentlemen

19:37.055 --> 19:38.754
you could ever imagine.

19:38.790 --> 19:40.690
He gave me stand-up
work, and he did the same

19:40.725 --> 19:43.626
for every one of them
boys outside that window.

19:43.661 --> 19:45.595
And he is struggling right now

19:45.630 --> 19:47.897
with the band and helping them grow.

19:47.932 --> 19:50.199
And if you arrest him,
all they'll be known for

19:50.235 --> 19:51.968
is arrest and violence.

19:52.003 --> 19:54.870
But if you let him go,

19:54.906 --> 19:56.372
he's gonna turn this group around.

19:56.407 --> 19:58.241
See, he is the soul of this group,

19:58.276 --> 20:01.377
and he is the future of
what music is gonna be.

20:01.412 --> 20:04.747
Ronnie Van Zant.

20:04.782 --> 20:07.283
He's gonna be one of
the greatest of them all.

20:07.318 --> 20:10.286
His music is gonna last forever.

20:12.123 --> 20:16.926
Now, you can help
him, or you can hurt him.

20:16.961 --> 20:18.194
It's in your hands.

20:24.469 --> 20:26.502
Well, you don't get the drugs back.

20:26.537 --> 20:28.237
Thank you.

20:28.273 --> 20:30.184
- Birth of Phil right there.
- [Milo] Fuck yeah, dude.

20:30.208 --> 20:31.941
- Right there, man.
- [Shelli] Hallelujah.

20:31.976 --> 20:33.676
[laughter]

20:33.711 --> 20:35.645
How did you feel about them using you

20:35.680 --> 20:37.346
to bring the drugs across the border?

20:37.382 --> 20:41.784
Truthfully, I felt disrespected.

20:41.819 --> 20:43.286
Hmm.

20:43.321 --> 20:46.155
And for a year or so,
I took work elsewhere.

20:46.190 --> 20:48.090
They left to make an
album with Tom Dowd,

20:48.126 --> 20:51.193
and I went to work with Pink Floyd.

20:51.229 --> 20:53.262
But I'd always hear from Ronnie,

20:53.298 --> 20:55.998
<i>my birthday, Christmas.</i>

20:56.034 --> 20:58.668
[telephone ringing]

20:58.703 --> 21:00.636
Production. This is Phil.

21:00.672 --> 21:02.204
[Ronnie] <i>How you doing there, Phil?</i>

21:02.240 --> 21:05.775
Ronnie, how's it going, man?

21:05.810 --> 21:08.010
Ohh, brother,

21:08.046 --> 21:10.646
<i>I don't want to go this
next round without you.</i>

21:10.682 --> 21:15.618
And I want you there when we open
up for the Rolling Stones.

21:15.653 --> 21:17.520
<i>Look, I don't need you for long, okay?</i>

21:17.555 --> 21:18.732
<i>We're going to
London at the end of summer,</i>

21:18.756 --> 21:20.022
<i>but we're gonna stop early.</i>

21:20.058 --> 21:21.290
I want you there, Phil,

21:21.326 --> 21:23.025
and, God damn it, you owe me.

21:23.061 --> 21:25.661
I rescued you from a life of
selling shitty Cuban cigars.

21:25.697 --> 21:27.530
I couldn't. My wife, she's...

21:27.565 --> 21:29.532
She would beat me.

21:29.567 --> 21:31.500
She's mean.

21:31.536 --> 21:33.302
I need your help, Phil.

21:33.338 --> 21:36.172
<i>♪ I paid my dues, and
I changed my style... ♪</i>

21:36.207 --> 21:37.340
You went, didn't you?

21:37.375 --> 21:38.641
Of course.

21:38.676 --> 21:41.243
[laughs] My boys, man, Skynyrd.

21:41.279 --> 21:42.978
Yes.

21:43.014 --> 21:46.248
[Phil] Well, Ronnie added another
guitarist, Steve Gaines,

21:46.284 --> 21:48.818
and his sister Cassie on vocals

21:48.853 --> 21:51.420
and two other singers
together called The Honkettes,

21:51.456 --> 21:54.190
and that band was on fire.

21:54.225 --> 21:56.392
<i>Everybody had an assignment.</i>

21:56.427 --> 21:58.561
Shut the fuck up.

21:58.596 --> 22:00.930
You boys are gonna
take this chance and do it.

22:00.965 --> 22:02.565
That's it.

22:02.600 --> 22:04.934
Otherwise, we can leave
it all alone right now.

22:04.969 --> 22:06.902
I realized something.

22:06.938 --> 22:08.904
I didn't get into this to be a footnote.

22:08.940 --> 22:11.841
I want all of us to be great together.

22:11.876 --> 22:13.409
Now, I didn't ask to be your daddy,

22:13.444 --> 22:15.544
but I will, and like
my daddy kicked my ass,

22:15.580 --> 22:17.046
I will kick your asses raw.

22:17.081 --> 22:19.682
Pull it together.

22:19.717 --> 22:22.284
Any one of you motherfuckers
who ain't built to go the distance,

22:22.320 --> 22:23.552
you just go right now.

22:23.588 --> 22:24.754
I ain't fucking around.

22:24.789 --> 22:28.023
Leave right now.

22:28.059 --> 22:30.359
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:30.395 --> 22:34.029
Good.

22:34.065 --> 22:36.432
Now, let's go kick the
fucking Rolling Stones'

22:36.467 --> 22:38.267
bony English asses.

22:38.302 --> 22:39.902
I love this story.

22:39.937 --> 22:42.438
Bill, you remember when
SHB opened for the Stones?

22:42.473 --> 22:45.708
Yeah, it was with Lenny
Kravitz and them in Virginia,

22:45.743 --> 22:47.154
and yeah, I remember it didn't go well.

22:47.178 --> 22:50.546
There was a nude guy sunbathing
two rows in.

22:50.581 --> 22:52.415
[Phil] Course there was.

22:52.450 --> 22:55.551
'Cause opening for the
Stones is the toughest gig in rock.

22:55.586 --> 22:57.920
It's like performing for a firing squad.

22:57.955 --> 22:59.655
Whoever you are,

22:59.690 --> 23:03.058
that audience does not give a fuck.

23:03.094 --> 23:06.128
And... but Ronnie said
to us one time, he said,

23:06.164 --> 23:11.000
"On any one day, any band can
be the greatest band in the world."

23:11.035 --> 23:14.236
And he wanted Lynyrd
Skynyrd's one day to be that day

23:14.272 --> 23:16.172
they opened for the Stones,

23:16.207 --> 23:19.809
and we trained for that
day like it was the Olympics,

23:19.844 --> 23:22.077
which it was in a way.

23:22.113 --> 23:25.514
He rebuilt that band and
was ready to take no prisoners,

23:25.550 --> 23:28.317
and he was gonna start by taking down

23:28.352 --> 23:30.352
the biggest band in the world.

23:30.388 --> 23:32.788
<i>We practiced every day for three weeks</i>

23:32.824 --> 23:36.358
<i>in a shack out in the country,
and there would be no drinking,</i>

23:36.394 --> 23:39.295
<i>there would be no fighting,
there'd be no messing around.</i>

23:39.330 --> 23:40.863
<i>Just pure magic.</i>

23:40.898 --> 23:43.432
The plan was to catch 'em by surprise.

23:43.468 --> 23:45.835
Let 'em fill the
dressing room with liquor.

23:45.870 --> 23:48.170
Let everybody think it
was gonna be a good old

23:48.206 --> 23:50.372
drunk and brawlin' Lynyrd Skynyrd.

23:50.408 --> 23:53.108
But when them boys showed up,

23:53.144 --> 23:56.879
they hit that stage on
all eight cylinders.

23:56.914 --> 23:58.848
And as the sun went down,

23:58.883 --> 24:01.383
<i>under a silly orange stage</i>

24:01.419 --> 24:03.953
<i>with that big Rolling Stones tongue</i>

24:03.988 --> 24:07.122
<i>they were not allowed to walk on,</i>

24:07.158 --> 24:11.393
<i>the full band delivered the
best show I have ever seen</i>

24:11.429 --> 24:13.128
<i>or will ever see.</i>

24:13.164 --> 24:15.364
<i>Eighty-five thousand people.</i>

24:15.399 --> 24:18.067
<i>Not one person left to piss.</i>

24:19.203 --> 24:22.338
They tore it up.

24:22.373 --> 24:23.739
[laughs]

24:25.042 --> 24:27.343
That's right.

24:27.378 --> 24:28.911
And there was Ronnie walking

24:28.946 --> 24:31.680
<i>between Allen, Gary, and Steve,</i>

24:31.716 --> 24:34.817
<i>runnin' the band, the
father figure, the coach,</i>

24:34.852 --> 24:36.519
<i>the leader.</i>

24:36.554 --> 24:38.888
<i>It was the birth of that
band as a global act,</i>

24:38.923 --> 24:40.556
<i>and you could see Ronnie.</i>

24:40.591 --> 24:42.358
<i>Soon as he knew they were killin' it,</i>

24:42.393 --> 24:44.159
<i>he's just pushin'
those boys further down</i>

24:44.195 --> 24:46.829
<i>that big orange
tongue, and I turned around,</i>

24:46.864 --> 24:48.998
<i>and I saw the whitest motherfucker</i>

24:49.033 --> 24:51.166
<i>I'd ever seen in my life.</i>

24:51.202 --> 24:55.504
This guy had no color at
all. And it was Mick Jagger.

24:55.540 --> 24:57.439
And he had to follow that.

24:57.475 --> 24:59.041
Shut the fuck up.

24:59.076 --> 25:00.843
Oh, my God.

25:00.878 --> 25:02.545
[Phil] It wasn't a performance.

25:02.580 --> 25:04.079
It was a street mugging.

25:04.115 --> 25:06.382
<i>Now, how do you top that?</i>

25:06.417 --> 25:07.917
<i>You just do.</i>

25:07.952 --> 25:09.552
<i>And you don't have to do it alone.</i>

25:09.587 --> 25:11.754
<i>You get there with
the help of your crew,</i>

25:11.789 --> 25:13.389
<i>everybody together,</i>

25:13.424 --> 25:15.291
band and crew.

25:15.326 --> 25:16.966
You can do anything.

25:18.563 --> 25:21.397
<i>And that kind of connection
only happens once or twice</i>

25:21.432 --> 25:22.731
<i>in a lifetime.</i>

25:25.836 --> 25:29.605
[cell phone chiming]

25:29.640 --> 25:31.807
That's weird.

25:31.842 --> 25:33.642
Hey, everything okay?

25:36.113 --> 25:38.047
Oh, God.

25:38.082 --> 25:41.383
Um, Sean's father passed away.

25:41.419 --> 25:42.651
Yeah, yeah, I'm here.

25:47.358 --> 25:49.792
I know, honey. I'm so sorry.

25:49.827 --> 25:52.828
I-I can't believe it either.

25:52.863 --> 25:54.263
Yeah.

25:54.298 --> 25:55.965
Just a sec.

25:58.035 --> 26:02.171
Um, yeah, okay, I'm... I'm
gonna try to get off the bus.

26:05.710 --> 26:07.109
Gooch, we got a problem.

26:07.144 --> 26:09.745
Shelli's got to fly home.

26:09.780 --> 26:12.514
Sean's father died.

26:12.550 --> 26:14.750
Yeah.

26:14.785 --> 26:17.786
Yeah, just got to get her
home. You got any ideas?

26:17.822 --> 26:20.689
We could get a flight
out of Redding Airport.

26:20.725 --> 26:22.591
We'll pull over in Weed.

26:22.627 --> 26:25.594
<i>[Cocteau Twins' "Iceblink Luck" playing]</i>

26:25.630 --> 26:30.633
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:42.980 --> 26:45.848
<i>♪ I'm seemin' to be ♪</i>

26:45.883 --> 26:49.718
<i>♪ A little alive... ♪</i>

26:49.754 --> 26:52.888
All right, I'll... I'll let you...

26:52.923 --> 26:54.490
[mouths word]

26:54.525 --> 26:56.725
Um, I'll... I'll call
you from the airport, okay?

26:56.761 --> 26:58.227
All right, bye.

26:58.262 --> 26:59.828
Hey, Bill.

26:59.864 --> 27:01.830
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:01.866 --> 27:04.533
<i>♪ Expose the daughter ♪</i>

27:04.568 --> 27:08.971
<i>♪ Of yourself well ♪</i>

27:09.006 --> 27:10.572
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:10.608 --> 27:14.143
<i>♪ Me, I think ♪</i>

27:14.178 --> 27:19.081
<i>♪ That you're in her heart ♪</i>

27:19.116 --> 27:20.816
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:20.851 --> 27:24.853
<i>♪ You're the match of Jericho ♪</i>

27:24.889 --> 27:26.355
<i>♪ That will burn... ♪</i>

27:26.390 --> 27:28.991
Uh, Kelly Ann?

27:29.026 --> 27:32.061
I just wanted to, uh... [laughs softly]

27:32.096 --> 27:36.098
I feel like I've been a
little bit of a, uh, clown.

27:36.133 --> 27:41.070
Oh, Milo.

27:41.105 --> 27:43.906
Yeah, I know.

27:43.941 --> 27:45.424
It's never gonna happen.

27:45.459 --> 27:49.244
Well, I want to be stirred
up and filled with passion.

27:49.280 --> 27:52.047
I mean, that's what
Phil's story is all about,

27:52.083 --> 27:54.066
passion and where it takes us and...

27:54.101 --> 27:57.953
I think Phil's story is about destiny,

27:57.988 --> 28:01.190
where it leads you.

28:01.225 --> 28:02.775
Do you take the path of the unknown,

28:02.810 --> 28:05.127
or do you just chicken
out and do whatever it takes

28:05.146 --> 28:06.712
to make the next dollar?

28:09.967 --> 28:11.550
Attention, store customers.

28:11.585 --> 28:13.202
This is the weed police.

28:13.237 --> 28:16.105
I will be confiscating all of
your marijuana this evening.

28:16.140 --> 28:17.923
God, I love weed.

28:17.958 --> 28:19.408
[laughs]

28:19.443 --> 28:20.893
Ooh, jerky.

28:20.928 --> 28:22.895
Try this one. This one. This one.

28:22.930 --> 28:24.791
<i>[Robyn Hitchcock's "The
Ghost In You" playing]</i>

28:24.815 --> 28:27.266
If you can just pop the
trunk, I got it, thanks.

28:27.301 --> 28:32.304
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:55.863 --> 28:57.663
<i>♪ A man in my shoes... ♪</i>

28:57.698 --> 29:00.165
Each one kills you in a different way.

29:00.201 --> 29:02.000
<i>♪ All the papers lie tonight... ♪</i>

29:02.036 --> 29:04.169
Right, Bill?

29:04.205 --> 29:06.939
Not like this, though.

29:06.974 --> 29:08.407
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:08.442 --> 29:12.461
<i>♪ Is the news of the day... ♪</i>

29:12.496 --> 29:15.347
Everybody's talking about
the tour ending.

29:15.382 --> 29:19.818
You know, Phil's story has me thinking.

29:19.854 --> 29:21.987
I don't know that I'm
built for this forever.

29:22.022 --> 29:24.673
The other day, I found this
old hard drive from when I was 16.

29:24.708 --> 29:26.592
And I read this
letter I wrote to myself.

29:26.627 --> 29:28.594
I mean, just incredible
stuff about dreams

29:28.629 --> 29:30.712
and what I wanted out of life.

29:30.748 --> 29:32.776
I mean, it was like the
child me grabbing the adult me

29:32.800 --> 29:36.335
by the collar and saying,
"Hey, be fucking bold."

29:36.387 --> 29:38.303
You know, it was
filled with such power, dude.

29:38.339 --> 29:40.455
I wanted to build a school in India.

29:40.474 --> 29:42.524
I was 16.

29:42.560 --> 29:44.810
And, you know, I
thought about it, and I said,

29:44.845 --> 29:47.679
"Okay, well, this used to
be me, and it still can be,"

29:47.715 --> 29:51.116
but I've piled so many
layers of shit and doubt over myself

29:51.152 --> 29:53.235
that I barely even recognize me.

29:53.270 --> 29:56.305
It was like I knew me
better before I was even me.

29:56.340 --> 29:58.051
I don't know; it was just an
amazing piece of writing.

29:58.075 --> 29:59.858
Of course it was. It was my hard drive.

29:59.894 --> 30:01.877
I wrote that about me.

30:01.912 --> 30:04.179
Shit. Are you kidding?

30:04.215 --> 30:05.480
No.

30:05.516 --> 30:08.217
No wonder it sounded
like me but... better.

30:08.252 --> 30:10.085
Because it was me.

30:10.120 --> 30:12.821
Even when you question your entire life,

30:12.857 --> 30:16.024
you are taking things from me.

30:16.060 --> 30:17.392
Well, here.

30:17.428 --> 30:19.161
You take it, then.

30:19.196 --> 30:20.863
It's awesome.

30:20.898 --> 30:23.332
You know, it's like the
story Phil's telling.

30:23.367 --> 30:26.869
Get connected with where you started.

30:26.904 --> 30:31.874
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:31.909 --> 30:34.610
So you think I'm a coward. Is that it?

30:34.645 --> 30:35.956
I don't know what you're talking about.

30:35.980 --> 30:37.946
I just heard what you said about me.

30:37.982 --> 30:40.215
I'm chickening out.

30:40.251 --> 30:42.084
I was talking about myself.

30:42.119 --> 30:44.119
I'm questioning shit.

30:44.154 --> 30:48.891
I know Laurie and our future
kid is my destiny, and I'm scared.

30:48.926 --> 30:51.026
Well, for your information,

30:51.061 --> 30:53.962
I'm fucking... lost.

30:53.998 --> 30:55.597
So there.

30:55.633 --> 30:57.033
I just said that to the sound girl.

30:57.067 --> 30:59.067
Do you have any idea what's going on?

30:59.103 --> 31:01.414
Look, I wish I had an answer for
you about the European leg.

31:01.438 --> 31:03.305
I'm not talking about that.

31:03.340 --> 31:05.207
I'm talking about Kelly Ann.

31:05.242 --> 31:06.843
She's right in front of you.

31:06.983 --> 31:08.277
Wake up.

31:12.116 --> 31:13.582
[Ronnie] <i>This is a song I wrote</i>

31:13.617 --> 31:15.617
<i>about the South, and I believe in it.</i>

31:15.653 --> 31:17.252
<i>And it goes something like this.</i>

31:17.288 --> 31:19.421
<i>[soft music playing]</i>

31:19.456 --> 31:21.790
Well, after the Rolling Stones victory,

31:21.825 --> 31:24.593
everything was all sweetness and light.

31:24.628 --> 31:28.297
<i>We marched into Tokyo like
an unbeatable army,</i>

31:28.332 --> 31:32.668
<i>and, my God, it felt good.</i>

31:32.703 --> 31:34.770
We all met down in the bar.

31:34.805 --> 31:37.906
Ronnie wanted some Dom
Perignon, but they didn't have it,

31:37.942 --> 31:40.008
<i>so he spent an enormous amount of money</i>

31:40.044 --> 31:42.577
<i>buying imported Jack
Daniel's for the house.</i>

31:42.613 --> 31:44.746
<i>All right, arigato, my friends.</i>

31:44.782 --> 31:47.749
<i>[together] Arigato.</i>

31:47.785 --> 31:49.952
- Sick.
- Now, this was the liftoff.

31:49.987 --> 31:51.853
This was the new chapter.

31:51.889 --> 31:56.158
Your rough-and-tumble John
Wayne American image is so famous.

31:56.193 --> 31:57.926
It's kind of an exaggeration.

31:57.962 --> 32:00.495
We got in fights, like any kid would.

32:00.531 --> 32:01.997
Yeah, we did that for a long time.

32:02.032 --> 32:03.376
You know, show me your biggest badass,

32:03.400 --> 32:05.100
and I got an
appointment with him outside.

32:05.135 --> 32:06.368
But no more.

32:06.403 --> 32:07.536
And we're not kids anymore.

32:07.571 --> 32:09.771
We're 27 and 28.

32:09.807 --> 32:12.374
Does your image make
it important for you

32:12.409 --> 32:14.276
to be angry at Neil Young?

32:14.311 --> 32:16.611
You're talking about
"Sweet Home Alabama."

32:16.647 --> 32:18.380
No, we love Neil Young.

32:18.415 --> 32:20.360
He just sent use some new
songs if we want to do 'em.

32:20.384 --> 32:22.184
[woman] Why do you perform barefoot?

32:22.219 --> 32:24.553
If I can't feel the fire
onstage, I know I failed.

32:24.588 --> 32:25.887
He just don't like shoes.

32:25.923 --> 32:27.456
[Ronnie] That's true.

32:27.491 --> 32:32.194
<i>♪ Sweet home Alabama ♪</i>

32:32.229 --> 32:36.898
<i>♪ Where the skies are so blue ♪</i>

32:36.934 --> 32:40.535
<i>♪ Sweet home Alabama... ♪</i>

32:40.571 --> 32:43.638
They killed their
shows in Tokyo and Osaka.

32:43.674 --> 32:46.174
And on that last night,

32:46.210 --> 32:48.977
I could swear that stage was on fire.

32:49.013 --> 32:51.880
Those boys could play like no one else.

32:51.915 --> 32:55.150
There were a raging, rolling machine.

32:55.185 --> 32:58.053
Ain't been nobody like 'em since.

32:59.690 --> 33:01.267
[Reg] <i>I just can't
get these figures to work.</i>

33:01.291 --> 33:03.058
It's like, with two
different band leaders,

33:03.093 --> 33:05.961
two different revenue
streams going outbound...

33:08.132 --> 33:12.067
...we can't afford another
leg, not with these expenses,

33:12.102 --> 33:15.203
especially not in Europe.

33:15.239 --> 33:17.839
No amount of cutting is going to work,

33:17.875 --> 33:20.842
unless you cut the pie in half.

33:20.878 --> 33:23.578
[laughs]

33:23.614 --> 33:26.715
[sighs] I'm going to bed.

33:26.750 --> 33:28.283
Good work.

33:28.318 --> 33:31.019
I know it wasn't easy.

33:31.055 --> 33:32.788
[exhales deeply]

33:35.092 --> 33:36.625
Good night.

33:38.495 --> 33:41.496
[women moaning]

33:51.809 --> 33:55.243
<i>Harris, what you just did will
help the world replenish.</i>

33:55.279 --> 33:58.146
<i>Look, I know it wasn't
easy having sex again,</i>

33:58.182 --> 34:00.949
<i>even if it was with the
most attractive women</i>

34:00.984 --> 34:02.951
<i>of the entire human species.</i>

34:02.986 --> 34:06.988
<i>Now... give me Jen.</i>

34:07.024 --> 34:09.524
[Rick] <i>Harris, we couldn't find her.</i>

34:10.828 --> 34:12.460
<i>I was just a pawn?</i>

34:13.996 --> 34:15.464
<i>I trusted you.</i>

34:15.498 --> 34:16.965
<i>How foolish.</i>

34:17.000 --> 34:20.335
<i>My silly need to fit in and be accepted.</i>

34:20.370 --> 34:22.437
<i>That's how you lure me in?</i>

34:22.473 --> 34:26.942
<i>But I'm here to serve a
bigger, more cynical plan.</i>

34:26.976 --> 34:30.178
<i>Why didn't I see through this?</i>

34:30.214 --> 34:32.914
<i>Because that's how they trick you.</i>

34:32.949 --> 34:36.083
<i>They take an average man</i>

34:36.120 --> 34:40.789
<i>and make him feel... beautiful.</i>

34:43.694 --> 34:45.627
I'm a pawn.

34:45.661 --> 34:48.797
Well, last night in
Tokyo, the promoter, Mr. Udo,

34:48.831 --> 34:50.931
took everybody to a Japanese disco

34:50.967 --> 34:54.034
that kind of catered to an
English-speaking clientele.

34:54.071 --> 34:57.706
The translation of the
name of the disco was, uh...

34:57.741 --> 35:00.175
Was "Casual Mind Universe,"

35:00.210 --> 35:03.545
whatever the fuck that's
supposed to mean.

35:03.580 --> 35:05.714
Everybody was in a good mood,

35:05.749 --> 35:08.116
<i>celebratory, loose.</i>

35:08.152 --> 35:11.119
[indistinct chatter]

35:11.155 --> 35:14.122
<i>[upbeat disco music playing]</i>

35:14.158 --> 35:17.425
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:19.663 --> 35:22.130
This reminds me of
the first time we met.

35:22.166 --> 35:23.532
Meet in all the best places.

35:23.567 --> 35:25.033
How you feeling, Ronnie?

35:25.068 --> 35:26.801
Never better.

35:26.837 --> 35:29.371
Things are going so well, I-I
just don't feel comfortable.

35:31.441 --> 35:33.408
I keep waiting for
something that's gonna

35:33.443 --> 35:35.210
just take it all away.

35:38.415 --> 35:40.048
[laughs]

35:40.083 --> 35:41.494
You know, at least when I
was drinking and fighting,

35:41.518 --> 35:43.685
I knew where the hurt would come from.

35:43.720 --> 35:45.220
I did it myself.

35:45.255 --> 35:46.721
Damn right.

35:46.757 --> 35:50.892
Now I-I feel so
protective, I just want to run away.

35:50.928 --> 35:52.727
But I can't.

35:52.763 --> 35:54.206
I'm Papa Ronnie.

35:55.587 --> 35:57.911
You... you know, I just don't
want my baby girl to grow up

35:57.935 --> 36:00.035
and read about me like I
was some fighting redneck.

36:00.070 --> 36:02.404
Hmm.

36:02.439 --> 36:04.005
I got this voice inside, man.

36:04.041 --> 36:06.608
I-it's just telling me, "Don't wait.

36:06.643 --> 36:08.109
We got to get there."

36:08.145 --> 36:10.779
I can't shake this feeling, Phil.

36:10.814 --> 36:13.181
What do you call it, huh?

36:13.217 --> 36:16.551
Oh, I know what they
call it, and I hate it.

36:16.587 --> 36:18.053
[both] Growing up.

36:18.088 --> 36:19.187
Let's go get a drink.

36:19.223 --> 36:20.722
Like grown-ups.

36:20.757 --> 36:23.725
Now, growing up is trying
to do the right thing.

36:23.760 --> 36:27.696
Problem is, doing the right thing

36:27.731 --> 36:29.631
sucks quite a bit of the time.

36:29.666 --> 36:32.234
Ronnie Van Zant said that.

36:32.269 --> 36:33.735
Yeah.

36:33.770 --> 36:36.238
He was my first real hero.

36:36.273 --> 36:38.540
And even heroes got to grow up.

36:38.575 --> 36:42.377
So what is it you wanted to ask me?

36:42.412 --> 36:45.614
[chuckles]

36:45.649 --> 36:48.984
Would you be the godfather of my son?

36:49.019 --> 36:52.254
Phil, that'd be my honor.

36:52.289 --> 36:53.989
You've been holding out on me.

36:54.024 --> 36:56.124
Mr. Udo kept sending over bottles

36:56.159 --> 36:58.260
of Dom Perignon to the table.

36:58.295 --> 37:01.296
[indistinct chatter]

37:02.866 --> 37:05.233
<i>A group of German airline
pilots appeared</i>

37:05.269 --> 37:06.768
at the next table,

37:06.803 --> 37:09.337
started to try to figure
out who the band was.

37:09.373 --> 37:10.639
[laughter]

37:10.674 --> 37:13.108
American rednecks Lynyrd Skynyrd.

37:13.143 --> 37:15.410
- Hey, Americans.
- Whoo!

37:15.445 --> 37:16.845
We got recognized.

37:16.880 --> 37:18.980
And then the shit hit the fan.

37:19.016 --> 37:20.415
[man] Big, strong Southern girls.

37:20.450 --> 37:21.683
We gonna take that shit?

37:21.718 --> 37:23.084
Yeah, we're gonna take that.

37:23.120 --> 37:24.753
This ain't Florida.

37:24.788 --> 37:27.489
Hey, Phil, what do you
really think about our band?

37:27.524 --> 37:29.658
Well, I've never seen a better band live.

37:29.693 --> 37:30.870
I've never felt more at
home than when I'm on your stage.

37:30.894 --> 37:32.260
Sorry, I can't quite hear you,

37:32.296 --> 37:34.362
'cause these
assholes are talking so loud.

37:34.398 --> 37:35.630
You're like my other family.

37:35.666 --> 37:38.099
[man] Girls are very pretty.

37:38.135 --> 37:39.701
[Allen] Hey, y'all better back off.

37:39.736 --> 37:42.470
Oh, they say you are the
tough guys from the South

37:42.506 --> 37:43.938
who like to fight.

37:43.974 --> 37:45.614
- Not no more.
- Your girls are so pretty.

37:45.642 --> 37:47.108
Do you screw them?

37:47.144 --> 37:49.377
[Phil] <i>This is where I
began to get nervous.</i>

37:49.413 --> 37:52.013
Dean leaned over and said...

37:52.049 --> 37:53.315
Phil, let's get out of here.

37:53.350 --> 37:54.949
Where's Mr. Udo?

37:54.985 --> 37:55.962
I don't know. I don't
want to leave the table.

37:55.986 --> 37:56.875
If any of you hit anyone,

37:56.876 --> 37:58.175
we'll never get you out of the country.

37:58.199 --> 37:59.559
[Gary] You know I got a mean left.

37:59.607 --> 38:00.824
What about getting out of the country?

38:00.825 --> 38:02.615
That was the deal getting you in
here, that we wouldn't fight.

38:02.639 --> 38:04.104
That's starting to become a problem.

38:04.105 --> 38:05.627
[man] Just talk to us.

38:05.662 --> 38:07.128
We like your girls.

38:07.164 --> 38:08.563
Don't be rude.

38:08.598 --> 38:10.365
The boys are busy. Thank you.

38:10.400 --> 38:12.000
They are not boys.

38:12.035 --> 38:15.236
They are big Southern
men, big, tough Southern men

38:15.272 --> 38:16.805
with girls with pretty titties.

38:16.840 --> 38:18.540
What if he hits me first? Can I hit him?

38:18.575 --> 38:20.353
- That's self-defense.
- Hey, just leave us alone.

38:20.377 --> 38:22.021
Okay, guys, the band
doesn't want to talk right now.

38:22.045 --> 38:23.357
We just played a big show.

38:23.467 --> 38:25.091
Because we are
German, you don't like us.

38:25.115 --> 38:27.082
- No, not at all.
- Oh, we just want to have fun.

38:27.117 --> 38:29.184
Can we please play with her titties?

38:29.219 --> 38:30.518
You shut the fuck up.

38:30.554 --> 38:33.254
- Hey, Ronnie.
- Well, we had a plan.

38:33.290 --> 38:35.390
- Don't fight.
- And it really worked...

38:35.425 --> 38:37.258
- Don't fight.
- Till it stopped working.

38:37.294 --> 38:39.561
But don't fight.

38:39.596 --> 38:42.864
<i>♪ Oh, it's the
Saturday night special ♪</i>

38:42.899 --> 38:44.499
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:44.534 --> 38:48.069
<i>♪ For $20 you can buy
yourself one too ♪</i>

38:48.105 --> 38:50.238
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:50.273 --> 38:51.573
Were you in the fight too?

38:51.608 --> 38:53.274
I was just trying to keep the peace.

38:53.310 --> 38:58.279
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:58.315 --> 38:59.948
[panting]

38:59.983 --> 39:02.183
- We got to get him out fast.
- Well, what do we do?

39:02.219 --> 39:03.618
I'll get Ronnie out the back.

39:03.653 --> 39:04.897
You go out the front
and distract the cops.

39:04.921 --> 39:05.887
What if I get arrested?

39:05.922 --> 39:07.122
I'll come take care of it.

39:07.157 --> 39:08.601
By the time they figure everything out,

39:08.625 --> 39:09.769
we'll have the whole
band out of the country.

39:09.793 --> 39:11.693
Here, put that on.

39:11.728 --> 39:13.194
Don't lose my hat.

39:13.230 --> 39:15.530
Let me look at you.

39:15.565 --> 39:16.564
You look good.

39:16.600 --> 39:19.734
[laughter]

39:19.770 --> 39:21.169
You don't look much like me.

39:22.973 --> 39:24.806
I'll get this back to you.

39:24.841 --> 39:27.308
You keep it.

39:27.344 --> 39:30.145
Now, go be me.

39:30.180 --> 39:31.312
How am I gonna do that?

39:31.348 --> 39:34.282
Follow your instincts.

39:34.317 --> 39:37.152
♪ Here we are, here
we are, here we go ♪

39:37.187 --> 39:39.254
♪ Here we go ♪

39:39.289 --> 39:42.223
♪ Rockin' all over the world ♪

39:42.259 --> 39:43.958
See ya on the other side, brother.

39:43.994 --> 39:46.995
[Phil] <i>That was the last
time I ever saw Ronnie.</i>

39:51.301 --> 39:52.467
Harvey.

39:52.502 --> 39:54.636
[sighs]

39:54.671 --> 39:56.438
What do you know about why I was hired?

39:56.473 --> 39:59.340
What?

39:59.376 --> 40:01.509
You once said that you were loyal.

40:03.480 --> 40:07.482
I need you to be loyal to me right now.

40:07.517 --> 40:08.950
What are you talking about?

40:08.985 --> 40:10.985
Come on, man.

40:12.322 --> 40:15.590
Come on.

40:15.625 --> 40:18.593
Preston wants Tom to go solo.

40:18.628 --> 40:19.928
Fuck.

40:19.963 --> 40:22.497
You didn't hear that from me.

40:22.532 --> 40:24.432
We had to show Tom the numbers

40:24.468 --> 40:27.268
that he can make more
money without Christopher.

40:27.304 --> 40:29.504
Mm.

40:29.539 --> 40:32.707
So no amount of savings I
found would ever have mattered?

40:32.742 --> 40:34.309
Mm-mm.

40:34.344 --> 40:36.478
Preston would have given
Tom the same result.

40:36.513 --> 40:37.779
Mm-hmm.

40:37.814 --> 40:40.782
<i>[gentle guitar music]</i>

40:40.817 --> 40:45.787
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:45.822 --> 40:50.725
I was brought in to break up the brand.

40:50.760 --> 40:53.962
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:53.997 --> 40:56.464
Well, three days in a Japanese jail

40:56.500 --> 40:59.467
will give you some time to think.

40:59.503 --> 41:02.170
They smuggled the real
Ronnie out of the country.

41:02.205 --> 41:05.373
I went home after the
lawyers did a little do-si-do.

41:05.408 --> 41:07.575
Took a year off to raise my kid.

41:07.611 --> 41:10.712
It was Ronnie's idea.

41:10.747 --> 41:12.080
I could have done both.

41:12.115 --> 41:14.015
I missed that band.

41:14.050 --> 41:17.018
Later that year, they
decided to get a private plane

41:17.053 --> 41:20.889
that was fairly cheap, a Convair 240.

41:20.924 --> 41:23.191
<i>The third one ever built,</i>

41:23.226 --> 41:26.261
<i>had 29,000 flight hours on it.</i>

41:26.296 --> 41:29.330
<i>It was a tired plane.</i>

41:29.366 --> 41:31.599
<i>Aerosmith and Peter
Frampton had both looked at it</i>

41:31.635 --> 41:34.102
<i>and turned it down.</i>

41:34.137 --> 41:36.137
The band was worried about it.

41:38.608 --> 41:43.611
The plane ran out of gas over
a swamp in Mississippi.

41:45.882 --> 41:50.018
Ronnie died instantly, and...

41:50.053 --> 41:54.441
so did... Steve
Gaines and Cassie Gaines,

41:54.569 --> 41:55.913
his sister.

41:56.065 --> 41:59.794
So did their assistant road
manager, Dean Kilpatrick,

41:59.829 --> 42:01.696
and two others.

42:01.731 --> 42:06.668
It was the first time
someone I'd known and loved died.

42:08.338 --> 42:12.974
And I still haven't gotten over it.

42:13.009 --> 42:17.178
'Cause I know in my gut if
I'd have been on the plane...

42:19.182 --> 42:20.782
...I might've saved people.

42:20.817 --> 42:23.585
I should've been on that plane.

42:28.458 --> 42:31.793
Allen Collins lived for many more years,

42:31.828 --> 42:35.163
and so did Leon Wilkeson, Ron Eckerman,

42:35.198 --> 42:37.165
Billy Powell.

42:37.200 --> 42:41.135
Gary Rossington still tours with
a version of Lynyrd Skynyrd

42:41.171 --> 42:45.440
with Ronnie's little
brother Johnny singing lead.

42:45.475 --> 42:49.577
I couldn't listen to
their music for 20 years.

42:49.613 --> 42:52.814
But I hear Ronnie's restless spirit

42:52.849 --> 42:55.016
talking to me every day.

42:55.051 --> 42:57.096
<i>[Lynyrd Skynyrd's "All I Can
Do Is Write About It" playing]</i>

42:57.120 --> 43:01.155
He was the father of that
band till the day he died,

43:01.191 --> 43:05.627
and when I feel sad about
what he might have become,

43:05.662 --> 43:08.796
probably the Merle
Haggard of his generation,

43:08.832 --> 43:11.666
I think about how a man
learns to become a father.

43:11.701 --> 43:14.369
<i>♪ But the things they
write about us is just a bore... ♪</i>

43:14.404 --> 43:17.672
How do you spend this
little dance with destiny?

43:17.707 --> 43:20.308
That's up to you.

43:20.343 --> 43:24.479
But when you find your
band, you find your band.

43:24.514 --> 43:28.149
And that was my band,

43:28.184 --> 43:29.917
Lynyrd Skynyrd.

43:32.322 --> 43:36.024
Years later, I found another band,

43:36.059 --> 43:37.725
and that's this band and this crew,

43:37.761 --> 43:39.661
the Staton-House Band.

43:39.696 --> 43:42.497
That's why I came back.

43:42.532 --> 43:44.632
I listen to a voice inside,

43:44.668 --> 43:48.703
and if I don't like ya, I tell ya.

43:48.738 --> 43:51.372
And if I love ya, I'll tell ya.

43:51.408 --> 43:54.809
But whatever that voice says, I listen.

43:54.844 --> 43:58.629
And I thank my friend Ronnie
Van Zant for that.

43:58.665 --> 44:00.882
<i>♪ Slowly creepin' ♪</i>

44:00.917 --> 44:03.484
<i>♪ Lord, take me and mine ♪</i>

44:03.520 --> 44:07.672
<i>♪ Before that comes ♪</i>

44:07.724 --> 44:10.692
[Wesley and Milo playing
gentle guitar music]

44:10.727 --> 44:14.996
<i>♪ ♪</i>

44:15.031 --> 44:19.600
♪ Well, Mama told me ♪

44:19.619 --> 44:23.538
♪ When I was young ♪

44:23.573 --> 44:27.675
♪ Said, "Sit beside me ♪

44:27.711 --> 44:31.779
♪ My only son" ♪

44:31.815 --> 44:35.383
♪ Said, "Listen closely ♪

44:35.418 --> 44:39.253
♪ To what I say ♪

44:39.289 --> 44:41.589
♪ And if you do this ♪

44:41.624 --> 44:46.127
♪ It'll help you some sunny day ♪

44:46.162 --> 44:48.796
♪ Oh, yes, it will" ♪

44:48.832 --> 44:53.835
